HARI SREENIVASAN: It's been more
than two
years since Russia invaded the
Ukrainian territory

32:28.747 --> 32:33.385 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of Crimea, home to a Muslim
population that
has suffered greatly through the
centuries.

32:33.418 --> 32:37.322 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Since the invasion, they are
under pressure
once more.

32:37.355 --> 32:41.960 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
From Kiev, special correspondent
Kira Kay
reports, our story produced in
partnership

32:41.993 --> 32:44.896 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
with the Bureau for
International Reporting.

32:44.930 --> 32:52.070 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KIRA KAY: Here in the main
mosque of Ukraine's
capital, Kiev, Imam Seram Arifov
leads Friday

32:52.103 --> 32:58.243 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
prayers for the city's Muslims,
but he is
more than 500 miles from his
home in Simferopol,

32:58.276 --> 33:00.111 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Crimea.

33:00.145 --> 33:03.114 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
IMAM SERAM ARIFOV, Ukraine
(through translator):
I was a teacher. We had a
private school.

33:03.148 --> 33:09.588 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We were teaching the Islamic
religious sciences.
We also taught the Koran. I had
to leave my

33:09.621 --> 33:17.395 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
homeland to continue my job in
more acceptable
conditions. We could not work in
Crimea anymore.

33:17.429 --> 33:20.665 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They didn't let the school
operate. They didn't
renew our license.

33:20.699 --> 33:27.739 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
KIRA KAY: "They" are the
Russians, who invaded
and annexed Crimea in march
2014. The imam

33:27.772 --> 33:33.211 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and about 100 members of the
congregation
are Crimean Tatars, a small
Muslim community

33:33.245 --> 33:36.147 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
with centuries of history in the
region.

33:36.181 --> 33:40.819 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But many found themselves on the
wrong side
of the new authorities, and now
they have,

33:40.852 --> 33:46.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in effect, become refugees in
their own country.
This young mother is one of
them.

33:46.892 --> 33:51.329 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WOMAN (through translator): I
had to quit
my studies. I was studying there
in high school,

33:51.363 --> 33:56.101 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but I had to grab my documents
and come here.
All our loved ones are still in
Crimea. We

33:56.134 --> 34:00.672 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are far away from our parents.
And it's difficult
to be away from our homeland.

34:00.705 --> 34:06.678 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KIRA KAY: Protests in Ukraine
led to the ouster
of pro-Russian President Viktor
Yanukovych

34:06.711 --> 34:13.184 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in early 2014, but Russia,
unhappy with the
loss of Yanukovych, took
advantage of the

34:13.218 --> 34:16.721 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
turmoil, reclaiming territory it
considered
its own.

34:16.755 --> 34:24.629 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A referendum was held in March
2014. Russian
authorities say 96 percent of
Crimean voters

34:24.663 --> 34:28.266 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
supported the annexation.

34:28.300 --> 34:32.771 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But Refat Chubarov, the
political leader of
the Crimean Tatars, believes
many Crimean

34:32.804 --> 34:37.742 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
residents were too intimidated
by the heavy
presence of Russian troops to
express their

34:37.776 --> 34:39.577 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
true feelings.

34:39.611 --> 34:41.379 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
REFAT CHUBAROV, Chairman, The
Mejlis of the
Crimean Tatar People (through
translator):

34:41.413 --> 34:45.684 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The only ones who spoke out
openly against
such a fake referendum were
Crimean Tatars.

34:45.717 --> 34:51.222 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We understood that Crimea faced
a new problem,
a terrible one. Moscow never
came to Crimea

34:51.256 --> 34:53.058 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
with good intentions.

34:53.091 --> 34:58.563 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KIRA KAY: The Crimean Tatars
already had a
long history of conflict with
Russia, going

34:58.596 --> 35:05.203 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
back even before the Soviet
Union. Then, during
World War II, nearly the entire
population

35:05.236 --> 35:11.476 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
was forcefully deported
thousands of miles
away by communist dictator
Joseph Stalin.

35:11.509 --> 35:17.882 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Ukraine says more than 100,000
people died
in what it considers a genocide.

35:17.916 --> 35:22.620 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
That history resurfaced
dramatically last
week, when a Ukrainian woman of
Crimean Tatar

35:22.654 --> 35:30.128 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
descent won a Pan-European sing
contest watched
by tens of millions. Her winning
song memorialized

35:30.161 --> 35:38.570 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the 1944 deportation of the
Tatars. Only after
the Soviet Union dissolved in
the 1990s and

35:38.603 --> 35:43.208 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ukraine became its own country
did the bulk
of Crimea's Tatars return, with
the hopes

35:43.241 --> 35:46.144 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of starting over.

35:46.177 --> 35:51.316 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Gulnara Izetovna's family
resettled and had
just finished building their new
house. But

35:51.349 --> 35:56.388 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
after the referendum, Gulnara
was stopped
by authorities when returning
from a trip.

35:56.421 --> 36:01.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GULNARA IZETOVNA, Ukraine
(through translator):
They asked about my nationality.
I was accused

36:01.593 --> 36:04.429 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
of separatism and they
interrogated me.

36:04.462 --> 36:10.001 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KIRA KAY: Izetovna fled, as have
an estimated
30,000 other Crimean Tatars.

36:10.035 --> 36:15.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GULNARA IZETOVNA (through
translator): Living
now in the 21st century, I never
thought that

36:15.340 --> 36:20.512 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this could happen again. What my
parents felt
during World War II is the same
thing I feel

36:20.545 --> 36:22.347 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
now.

36:22.380 --> 36:27.085 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
KIRA KAY: Ukraine is an
overwhelmingly Christian
country. The Orthodox Church
plays a strong

36:27.118 --> 36:32.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
role in life here. But the
annexation of Crimea,
and the Russian support of
separatists in

36:32.791 --> 36:38.396 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the east of the country, has
created a shared
enemy and made Ukraine more
welcoming of thousands

36:38.430 --> 36:42.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of Muslim refugees than some
other parts of
Europe.

36:42.033 --> 36:46.638 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Still, it has been a difficult
process, says
aid worker Enver Bekirov.

36:46.671 --> 36:52.644 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ENVER BEKIROV, Aid Worker
(through translator):
There were many large families
of Crimean

36:52.677 --> 36:58.316 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tatars, families with sick
people, disabled
people. We just decided to take
the responsibility.

36:58.349 --> 37:03.621 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KIRA KAY: Bekirov ensures the
displaced have
proper clothing and food, and
helps them find

37:03.655 --> 37:07.892 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
housing that various refugee
agencies also
pay for.

37:07.926 --> 37:13.698 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When Lenie Bilial fled Crimea,
she was pregnant
with her sixth child. She and
her husband,

37:13.731 --> 37:17.669 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mustafa, had wanted to stay in
Crimea, but
felt repressed because of their
faith.

37:17.702 --> 37:21.106 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MUSTAFA BILIAL, Ukraine (through
translator):
We are Muslims, and this is very
important

37:21.139 --> 37:25.643 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to us. What is happening in
Russia, we see
that Muslims are being
persecuted. They come

37:25.677 --> 37:30.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and break into these educational
establishments.
They include certain literature
on the blacklist.

37:30.415 --> 37:34.219 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I worry, for example, the Koran
or other books
might end up on the list.

37:34.252 --> 37:41.092 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KIRA KAY: Today, they feel
welcomed by their
new neighbors, but also not
fully at home.

37:41.126 --> 37:45.864 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Back in Crimea, Russian
authorities are now
intensifying their crackdown on
the Tatars,

37:45.897 --> 37:51.569 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
arresting activists and
community leaders
by using anti-extremist laws.
Others have

37:51.603 --> 37:56.574 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
been abducted, including this
man, who was
filmed being taken by a
pro-Russian militia

37:56.608 --> 38:00.445 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and was later found dead with
signs of torture.

38:00.478 --> 38:06.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Crimean Tatars' governing
body, the Mejlis,
has been banned. They are now
functioning

38:06.317 --> 38:14.225 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in exile. Leader Refat Chubarov
has himself
been indicted by Crimean
prosecutors for violating

38:14.259 --> 38:18.963 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Russia's territorial integrity
by continuing
to insist Crimea is part of
Ukraine.

38:18.997 --> 38:23.434 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GEOFFREY PYATT, U.S. Ambassador
to Ukraine:
This is a moderate Muslim
community that was

38:23.468 --> 38:29.140 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
victimized once before under
Stalin and is
now being victimized under the
Russian occupation

38:29.174 --> 38:31.042 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of Crimea.

38:31.075 --> 38:35.213 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KIRA KAY: Geoffrey Pyatt is the
American ambassador
to Ukraine. The U.S. has
sanctions against

38:35.246 --> 38:40.518 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Russia because of the Crimean
annexation.
Pyatt says that amidst the
diplomatic pressure

38:40.552 --> 38:43.988 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and war of words, Crimea's
Tatars shouldn't
be overshadowed.

38:44.022 --> 38:48.927 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GEOFFREY PYATT: Crimea is not
going to be
returned to Ukrainian
sovereignty over the

38:48.960 --> 38:55.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
short-term. And the Tatar
community understands
that. To have a community like
the Tatars,

38:55.433 --> 39:00.438 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
which is notably tolerant,
notably inclusive,
makes it even more important
that we not allow

39:00.471 --> 39:02.840 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
their story to be forgotten.

39:02.874 --> 39:09.647 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KIRA KAY: Recently, Crimean
Tatars have taken
dramatic steps to make sure they
aren't forgotten.

39:09.681 --> 39:14.886 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Last year, they created a
blockade of the
roads leading from Ukraine into
Crimea, jamming

39:14.919 --> 39:17.288 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
an economic lifeline.

39:17.322 --> 39:22.927 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And activists believed to
include Crimean
Tatars blew up the power lines
still serving

39:22.961 --> 39:28.967 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Crimea, plunging the peninsula
into darkness
for weeks. But most Crimean
Tatars acknowledge

39:29.000 --> 39:35.340 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they won't be going home any
time soon, including
journalist Osman Pashayev, who
had been detained

39:35.373 --> 39:39.143 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
while covering commemorations of
the historic
deportation.

39:39.177 --> 39:45.750 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, he and his entire news staff
also went
into exile. Their small
operation keeps the

39:45.783 --> 39:50.688 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
flow of free information, both
for the community
in exile and those back home.

39:50.722 --> 39:53.591 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
OSMAN PASHAYEV, Editor, ATR
Television (through
translator): We're looking
something to keep

39:53.625 --> 39:58.896 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that connection. We have to be
relevant to
our audience, and we must avoid
that the annexation

39:58.930 --> 40:00.598 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
becomes permanent.

40:00.632 --> 40:06.237 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KIRA KAY: But with every passing
day, that
connection may become harder to
keep.

40:06.271 --> 40:15.647 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is Kira Kay for "PBS
NewsHour" in Kiev,
Ukraine.

40:15.680 --> 40:26.190 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: It seems as if
there are important
breakthroughs each year in the
field of genetics

40:26.224 --> 40:31.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and medicine. In many ways, we
indeed could
be on the verge of historical
changes in how

40:31.529 --> 40:35.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we use DNA and how we edit our
biological
code.

40:35.933 --> 40:41.205 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the moment can be deceptive.
The history
of genetics is long and
complicated, dating

40:41.239 --> 40:46.878 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
back to the mid-19th century.
It's full of
exciting discoveries, endless
mysteries and

40:46.911 --> 40:48.680 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
even nefarious intent.

40:48.713 --> 40:54.419 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's the ambitious scope of a
new book,
"The Gene: An Intimate History."
Its author

40:54.452 --> 40:59.957 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is Dr. Siddhartha Mukherjee, a
cancer physician
and an assistant professor of
medicine at

40:59.991 --> 41:05.663 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Columbia University. He's the
author of the
Pulitzer Prize-winning "The
Emperor of All

41:05.697 --> 41:08.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Maladies: A Biography of
Cancer."

41:08.299 --> 41:10.335 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Dr. Siddhartha Mukherjee,
welcome to the "NewsHour"
again.

41:10.368 --> 41:11.936 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. SIDDHARTHA MUKHERJEE,
Author, "The Gene:
An Intimate History": Pleasure
to be here.

41:11.969 --> 41:13.805 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Thank you.

41:13.838 --> 41:17.608 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, an intimate
history within
what? Just a short time after
you have come

41:17.642 --> 41:23.881 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
out with this award-winning book
on cancer,
you tackle an arguably more
complicated subject,

41:23.915 --> 41:27.585 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
the gene, and there is a
personal connection.
Explain that.

41:27.618 --> 41:29.587 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. SIDDHARTHA MUKHERJEE: Well,
this book
took actually a long time to
write. It was

41:29.620 --> 41:32.623 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
-- it took six years to write
this book.

41:32.657 --> 41:38.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the book gets intimate right
from the
first page. The story opens
really with an

41:38.730 --> 41:42.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
exploration that was in the back
of my mind
where I -- as I was growing up.
It was about

41:42.433 --> 41:48.072 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
my family's mental illness, two
uncles consumed
by schizophrenia and bipolar
disease, and

41:48.106 --> 41:53.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
then, one generation later,
another, so, on
the same side of the family,
also diagnosed

41:53.077 --> 41:57.715 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
with schizophrenia and
institutionalized,
and the growing realization in
my mind as

41:57.749 --> 42:03.788 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a child that this wasn't --
there was some
heredity lurking, that genes
were lurking

42:03.821 --> 42:07.492 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
behind mental illness, and that
coming to
fullness as I started to study
medicine and

42:07.525 --> 42:11.362 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
realize that there was a genetic
core to all
of this.

42:11.396 --> 42:15.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You sense, in
reading this
book, that there is an urgency
to this, that

42:15.833 --> 42:18.403 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you felt it was important to get
this done
now. Why?

42:18.436 --> 42:21.706 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. SIDDHARTHA MUKHERJEE: It's
important to
get this done now because we are
at the -- on

42:21.739 --> 42:27.345 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the verge of unveiling or
discovering and
inventing astonishing new
technologies that

42:27.378 --> 42:30.415 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
allow us to read and write human
genomes.

42:30.448 --> 42:35.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And let me explain what I mean.
By read, I
mean we can now begin to scan
the human genome,

42:35.319 --> 42:40.124 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
your genome, mine, all the genes
that you
and I have, and ask questions
about what it

42:40.158 --> 42:42.226 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
predicts for us in the future.

42:42.260 --> 42:46.898 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The technology is far from
accurate, but,
for instance, the risk of breast
cancer may

42:46.931 --> 42:52.737 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
be present in a variation in
your genome.
And by write, I mean something
even more strange,

42:52.770 --> 42:56.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
which is that, lately -- and
this has been
widely covered, but, lately, we
have been

42:56.441 --> 43:01.045 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
able to -- scientists have been
able to go
into the human genome and make
intentional

43:01.078 --> 43:06.217 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
alterations, erase genes, change
genes, change
their content, et cetera.

43:06.250 --> 43:12.390 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's a surprising thing to do
and portends
a very, very complex landscape
for the future.

43:12.423 --> 43:15.092 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And you do get to
some of these
very tough questions.

43:15.126 --> 43:18.863 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But you also -- you really go
back through
the history of genetics, all the
way back

43:18.896 --> 43:24.035 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to Aristotle and even before
that, I guess,
Pythagoras, move ahead to
Charles Darwin.

43:24.068 --> 43:27.738 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There are a number of figures
along the way
you spend time on.

43:27.772 --> 43:29.607 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Is one of them more important
than all the
others?

43:29.640 --> 43:32.276 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. SIDDHARTHA MUKHERJEE: Well,
they're all
important. This is a story
knitted together

43:32.310 --> 43:34.679 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
with other stories.

43:34.712 --> 43:40.117 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I wanted to keep things
simple enough,
so that all readers could get --
you know,

43:40.151 --> 43:46.290 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the average reader, I could
understand what
the lineage of inventions and
discoveries

43:46.324 --> 43:48.226 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
was.

43:48.259 --> 43:52.597 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the most important
figures, of course,
is Gregor Mendel, a monk who
sort of persisted

43:52.630 --> 43:58.469 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with his experiments on pea
flowers and pea
plants, and just using those
very, very simple

43:58.503 --> 44:04.342 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
experiments really brought out
what was at
that time a revolutionary
understanding that

44:04.375 --> 44:10.081 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
units of carrying hereditary
traits or features
were moving between parents and
their children.

44:10.114 --> 44:17.021 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
That was a striking -- a
striking and original
observation, so striking, so
original, Judy,

44:17.054 --> 44:21.893 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that he -- that it was lost, the
